questionCode:
LazyColumn {
    items(comments.map { it.text }, key = { it }) { text ->
        CommentCard(text)
    }
}

answerCode:
Solution,
 🔨

At first glance, it looks like we‚Äôre doing everything right: we‚Äôre using the key parameter in items(), and we‚Äôre rendering a stable list.

But here‚Äôs the gotcha: we‚Äôre keying the list by the comment text, not by the actual unique identity of each comment.

If two comments have the same text ‚Äî which is common in real apps ‚Äî the key is no longer unique. This leads to Compose treating different items as the same, resulting in a crash when when a duplicate key is found as the list is being scrolled.

Fix: Always use a true stable identifier, like a comment ID: LazyColumn {
    items(comments, key = { it.id }) { comment ->
        CommentCard(comment.text)
    }
}

